<chapter xml:id="ch-learning-progressions">
 <title>Understanding Data Science Learning Progressions</title>


 <introduction>
   <p>
     This is a text to get a pull request from github. Data science learning progressions provide a roadmap for developing students' data literacy from kindergarten through grade 12. These progressions are organized into five interconnected strands that together form a comprehensive framework for data science education. Understanding these progressions will help you identify where your students are in their data science journey and plan instruction that builds systematically toward more sophisticated data practices.
   </p>
 </introduction>


 <section xml:id="sec-five-strands">
   <title>The Five Strands of Data Science Learning</title>


   <subsection xml:id="subsec-strand-a">
     <title>Strand A: Data Literacy and Responsibility</title>
    
     <p>
       <term>Focus:</term> This strand establishes the foundational understanding of what data is and how it should be approached responsibly. It emphasizes that data is created by people, contains inherent variability, and provides only partial information about the world.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Why It Matters:</term> In our data-driven society, students need to understand not just how to work with data, but what data represents and the ethical considerations involved in its collection and use. This strand develops critical thinking about data sources, biases, and the power dynamics involved in data work. Students learn to approach data with both curiosity and healthy skepticism.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Key Progressive Elements:</term>
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>K-2:</term> Students begin by recognizing that data can answer questions and that there are different types of information we can collect
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>3-5:</term> Students understand that data is created by people making decisions about what to measure and how
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>6-8:</term> Students recognize limitations in data and begin to identify bias and ethical considerations
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>9-10:</term> Students analyze how data collection methods affect interpretation and develop strategies for responsible data use
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>11-12:</term> Students critically evaluate data sources, understand complex ethical implications, and take agency in their own data practices
     </p>
   </subsection>


   <subsection xml:id="subsec-strand-b">
     <title>Strand B: Creation and Curation</title>
    
     <p>
       <term>Focus:</term> This strand covers where data comes from and how it should be collected, organized, and formatted to be useful. It encompasses both creating new data and working with existing datasets, emphasizing that real-world data is often messy and requires careful curation.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Why It Matters:</term> Students need to understand that high-quality analysis begins with high-quality data. This strand teaches students to be thoughtful about data collection methods, to recognize and address data quality issues, and to organize data in ways that facilitate meaningful analysis. These skills are essential for both consuming and producing reliable data-based conclusions.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Key Progressive Elements:</term>
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>K-2:</term> Students collect and organize simple data using basic tools like counting and sorting
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>3-5:</term> Students design simple investigations and organize data in tables with multiple attributes
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>6-8:</term> Students learn to clean data, identify errors and missing values, and work with more complex data structures
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>9-10:</term> Students design sophisticated data collection methods, work with multiple datasets, and understand sampling and bias
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>11-12:</term> Students develop comprehensive data management systems and work with complex, real-world datasets requiring advanced cleaning and organization
     </p>
   </subsection>


   <subsection xml:id="subsec-strand-c">
     <title>Strand C: Analysis and Modeling Techniques</title>
    
     <p>
       <term>Focus:</term> This strand develops students' ability to analyze data using various techniques, from basic summary statistics to complex modeling approaches. It emphasizes understanding which techniques to use for different types of data and questions, and includes both traditional statistical methods and modern computational approaches.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Why It Matters:</term> Analysis transforms raw data into insights. This strand ensures students can move beyond simply describing data to identifying patterns, relationships, and trends that inform decision-making. As data becomes increasingly complex and abundant, students need both conceptual understanding and practical skills with digital tools.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Key Progressive Elements:</term>
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>K-2:</term> Students describe data using simple comparisons and identify basic patterns through sorting and grouping
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>3-5:</term> Students calculate simple summary statistics and use digital tools to create basic visualizations
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>6-8:</term> Students work with measures of center and spread, identify relationships between variables, and begin using advanced digital tools
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>9-10:</term> Students conduct statistical analyses, work with correlation and regression, and use simulation methods
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>11-12:</term> Students apply advanced statistical techniques, work with machine learning concepts, and create sophisticated models
     </p>
   </subsection>


   <subsection xml:id="subsec-strand-d">
     <title>Strand D: Interpreting Problems and Results</title>
    
     <p>
       <term>Focus:</term> This strand focuses on making and justifying claims from data within appropriate contexts. It emphasizes understanding the relationship between questions, data, and valid conclusions, including the limitations of what can be inferred from any dataset.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Why It Matters:</term> The ability to draw valid conclusions from data is perhaps the most important skill in our information-rich world. This strand teaches students to think probabilistically, understand uncertainty, and communicate findings appropriately. It also develops skills in identifying when data supports or contradicts claims made by others.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Key Progressive Elements:</term>
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>K-2:</term> Students make simple claims based on data and recognize that different conclusions might be drawn from the same information
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>3-5:</term> Students begin using probabilistic language and understand that conclusions should be supported by evidence
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>6-8:</term> Students learn to qualify their conclusions with appropriate uncertainty language and recognize correlation versus causation
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>9-10:</term> Students apply formal statistical concepts, understand sampling and generalization, and evaluate the strength of evidence
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>11-12:</term> Students use advanced statistical inference, understand complex experimental design, and critically evaluate claims in media and research
     </p>
   </subsection>


   <subsection xml:id="subsec-strand-e">
     <title>Strand E: Visualization and Communication</title>
    
     <p>
       <term>Focus:</term> This strand develops students' ability to create effective visualizations and communicate findings to different audiences. It encompasses both the technical skills of creating graphs and charts and the communication skills needed to tell compelling, accurate stories with data.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Why It Matters:</term> Data visualization is both a tool for analysis and a medium for communication. Students need to understand how different visual representations highlight different aspects of data, and how to choose appropriate formats for their audiences and purposes. In a world filled with data visualizations, students also need to be critical consumers who can identify misleading or inappropriate visual representations.
     </p>
    
     <p>
       <term>Key Progressive Elements:</term>
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>K-2:</term> Students create simple visual representations like pictographs and bar charts using hands-on materials
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>3-5:</term> Students use digital tools to create basic visualizations and begin connecting visuals to narratives
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>6-8:</term> Students create more complex visualizations, understand design principles, and adapt their communication for different audiences
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>9-10:</term> Students create sophisticated multi-variable visualizations, understand advanced design principles, and use data for advocacy
     </p>
     <p>
       <term>11-12:</term> Students create publication-quality visualizations, understand accessibility considerations, and communicate complex analyses to diverse audiences
     </p>
   </subsection>
 </section>


 <section xml:id="sec-strands-together">
   <title>How the Strands Work Together</title>
  
   <p>
     These five strands are not meant to be taught in isolation. Instead, they represent different aspects of data science practice that should be integrated throughout instruction. A single data science investigation might involve:
   </p>
  
   <p>
     <term>Strand A concepts</term> when considering the source and limitations of data
   </p>
   <p>
     <term>Strand B skills</term> when collecting and organizing the dataset
   </p>
   <p>
     <term>Strand C techniques</term> when analyzing patterns and relationships
   </p>
   <p>
     <term>Strand D reasoning</term> when interpreting results and making claims
   </p>
   <p>
     <term>Strand E communication</term> when sharing findings with others
   </p>
  
   <p>
     The learning progressions show how each strand develops sophistication over time, but students at any grade level can engage with concepts from all five strands at an appropriate level of complexity.
   </p>
 </section>


 <section xml:id="sec-progressions-reflection">
   <title>Reflection and Self-Assessment</title>
  
   <exercise xml:id="ex-matching-concepts">
     <title>Part 1: Matching Concepts to Strands</title>
     <statement>
       <p>
         For each concept below, identify which strand (A, B, C, D, or E) it primarily belongs to. Write the letter of the strand in the space provided.
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 1. Understanding that all data contains some level of bias
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 2. Creating effective graphs that clearly communicate findings to an audience
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 3. Deciding whether a sample size is large enough to draw conclusions about a population
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 4. Organizing messy data into a clean, usable format
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 5. Calculating measures of center like mean and median
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 6. Recognizing that data represents decisions made by people
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 7. Using correlation and regression to identify relationships between variables
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 8. Evaluating whether claims made in the media are supported by the presented data
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 9. Designing an investigation to collect data that will answer a specific question
       </p>
      
       <p>
         _____ 10. Creating visualizations that are accessible to people with disabilities
       </p>
      
       <p>
         <em>Answer Key: 1-A, 2-E, 3-D, 4-B, 5-C, 6-A, 7-C, 8-D, 9-B, 10-E</em>
       </p>
     </statement>
   </exercise>


